interested readers to pursue the ideas in them further.  The list
below contains a selected list of review papers and overviews that may
be of interest to some students at the CSSS.  None of these are
required, and many touch upon topics that I won't discuss in my
lectures.  It might be fun to form groups to read and some of these
papers together.<p>-->


<!--<h4>General overviews and review</h4>

<ul>

<li> <a href="http://www.santafe.edu/~chaos">J. P. Crutchfield</a>, <a
href="http://www.santafe.edu/projects/CompMech/papers/wlboac.html">What
Lies Between Order and Chaos?</a> in Art and Complexity, J. Casti,
editor, Oxford University Press (2002). <i>An interesting,
non-technical essay discussing how new patterns are discovered, and
how complexity arises from the interplay between order and chaos.</I>
<p>

<li> <a href="http://www.santafe.edu/~chaos">J. P. Crutchfield</a>, <a
      href="http://www.santafe.edu/projects/CompMech/papers/EverNewTitlePage.html">Is
      Anything Ever New?</a> Considering Emergence, in
      Complexity: Metaphors, Models, and Reality, G. Cowan, D. Pines,
      and D. Melzner, editors, SFI Series in the Sciences of
      Complexity XIX, Addison-Wesley, Redwood City (1994) 479-497.  
      <i>This essay is a review of an approach to defining and then
      detecting the emergence of complexity in nonlinear processes. It
      is a non-technical synopsis of a longer, more technical paper,
      The Calculi of Emergence, which is listed below.</i><p>


<li>G. W. Flake, <a
href="http://mitpress.mit.edu/books/FLAOH/cbnhtml/home.html">The
Computational Beauty of Nature:  Computer Explorations of Fractals, Chaos,
Complex Systems, and Adaptation</a>.  MIT Press. 1998.  <i>An
excellent introduction to the central models and ideas of complex
systems.  Technical in places, but very accessible and very clear.
Highly recommended.</i><p>

<li>S. A. Levin.  <a
href="http://www.princeton.edu/~seasplan/lifesciences/Bulletin%20Am%20Math%20Soc.pdf">Complex
Adaptive Systems:  Exploring the known, the
unknown, and the unknowable</a>.  Bulletin of the American Mathematical 
Society.  40:3-19.  2002.  <i>I've only skimmed this.  Appears to be a
nice review of complex adaptive systems in the context of evolutionary
ecology.</i> <p>

<li><a href="http://cob.jmu.edu/rosserjb/">J.B. Rosser</a>.  <a
href="http://cob.jmu.edu/rosserjb/GENERIC.CPX.doc">On the
Complexities of Complex Economic Dynamics</a>. 
Journal of Economic Perspectives.  13:169-192.  1999.  <i>I've only
read about half of this.  It strikes me as a thorough, even-handed
review of the applications of "complexity theory" to economics.
Presents good spectrum of views, from those who think complexity is
mostly hype, to those who believe it has contributed significant new
understandings.  Contains around 125 references.</I> <a
href="http://ideas.repec.org/a/aea/jecper/v13y1999i4p169-192.html">pdf
format, for AEA members</a><p>

</ul>

<p><br>
<h4>Somewhat more technical papers and books</h4>

<ul>

<li>R. Badii and A. Politi.  <i>Complexity: Hierarchy structures and
scaling in physics</i>.   Cambridge.  1997.  <i>Thorough text of
different approaches to complexity.  Has a physics focus but contains
much of general interest and applications to a number of different
fields.  Clear and thorough.  More focused than the book by Flake (and
hence a little less general), and more technically demanding at times.
Highly recommended.</i><p>

<li>  <a href="http://www.santafe.edu/~chaos">J. P. Crutchfield</a>
and  <a href="http://hornacek.coa.edu/dave">D.P. Feldman</a>, <a
href="http://hornacek.coa.edu/dave/Publications/RURO.html"> 
Regularities Unseen, Randomness Observed: The Entropy Convergence
Hierarchy</a>.  <i>Chaos</i>, <b>15</b>: 25-54. 2003.  <i>Thorough
application of excess entropy and other measures of entropy
convergence to a wide range of stochastic processes.  Contains
thorough review of information theory, excess entropy, etc. </i><p>

<li> <a href="http://hornacek.coa.edu/dave">D.P. Feldman</a> and <a
	href="http://www.santafe.edu/~chaos">J. P. Crutchfield</a>,
	<a href="http://hornacek.coa.edu/dave/Publications/DNCO.html">
	Discovering Non-critical 
Organization: Statistical Mechanical, Information Theoretic, 
and Computational Views of Patterns in Simple One-Dimensional
Spin Systems</a>.  Santa Fe Institute Working Paper 98-04-026.  <i>A
review of computational mechanics and information theory and a
comparision with quantities from statistical mechanics.  Contains
detailed results for one-dimensinal Ising models.  Written especially
for people with a background in statistical mechanics, but should be
accessible to others as well.</i>
<p>

<li> <a href="http://www.santafe.edu/~chaos">J. P. Crutchfield</a>,
<a
href="http://www.santafe.edu/projects/CompMech/papers/CalcEmergTitlePage.html">The
Calculi of Emergence: Computation, Dynamics, and Induction</a>,
Physica D 75 (1994) 11-54. <i>An excellent overview of computational
mechanics.  A nice introductory section motivating why one needs
special tools to study emergence.  Contains many illustrative
examples. Highly recommended.</i><p> 


<li>  <a href="http://hornacek.coa.edu/dave">D.P. Feldman</a>and <a
href="http://www.santafe.edu/~chaos">J. P. Crutchfield</a>,  <a
href="Publications/MSCW.html"> Statistical Measures of Complexity:
Why?</a> Physics Letters A, <b>238</b>:(4-5), 244-252, 1998.  <i>A
short, not too technical paper critiquing several complexity
measures.</i><p> 

<li> <a
href="http://www.cscs.umich.edu/~crshalizi/">C. R. Shalizi</a>,
<a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/nlin.AO/0307015">Methods and Techniques
of Complex Systems Science: An Overview</a>.  In Thomas S.
  Deisboeck, J. Yasha Kresh and Thomas B. Kepler (eds.), <i>Complex Systems
  Science in Biomedicine</i> (Kluwer).  2004. <i>An excellent,
  thorough review.  Covers many tools: statistical learning and model
  selection; time series analysis; cellular automata; agent-based
  models; the evaluation of complex-systems models; information
  theory; and ways of measuring complexity.  Contains 265 references.
  Highly recommended.</i><p>


<li><a href="http://www.cscs.umich.edu/~crshalizi/">C. R. Shalizi</a>, 
<a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/cond-mat/9907176">Computational
Mechanics: Pattern and Prediction, Structure and Simplicity</a>.
<i>Journal of Statistical Physics</i>  104:816-879.  2001.
<i>Thorough, rigorous treatment of computational mechanics.
Recommended for those who want to understand the mathematical
underpinnings of causal states and computational mechanics</i>.

</ul>

<br>
